data.content:
Sir G. Lane's house
Sir George Lane intends to agree on renting a house for L400 fine and L46 rent per year.

Thomas Pepys
Thomas Pepys is referred to as "my coz," and they discuss the uncle's will in detail.

Sir G. Lane
Sir George Lane appears by chance at a house where the narrator and his friend are walking, showing interest in hiring it.

my wife
My wife is mentioned as being in bed when she tells me about our stolen silver tankard, and later as accompanying me to Whitehall.<SEP>The narrator's spouse, who assists in settling matters and shares concerns about her brother Balty's condition.<SEP>The narrator's wife is mentioned as being unwell, which affected their plans and activities over several days.<SEP>The narrator’s wife accompanied him on various visits and outings, including to the Wardrobe, the Mitre, and the Opera, showing interest in social events and theater performances but not actively seeking new acquaintances according to Lady Batten's perception.

cozen Thomas Pepys
Cozen Thomas Pepys is an acquaintance of the narrator who discusses estate matters with him.

24th
This date marks the beginning of a series of diary entries focusing on personal and business matters.

silver tankard
The silver tankard was stolen from the narrator's home, causing vexation due to negligence in securing the door.

the Wardrobe
The narrator visits the Wardrobe but arrives too late, indicating it is an important place in his routine.<SEP>This is a place where the narrator visits multiple times, possibly for social engagements or administrative matters.<SEP>The narrator and his wife visited the Wardrobe, a place known for its social gatherings or possibly a noble’s residence they frequently visit.

servants
The narrator dines with his servants at one point during the day.

my Lady
My Lady refers to a noblewoman who shows favor and hospitality to the narrator and his wife, which he appreciates.<SEP>Refers to a lady whose health and condition were discussed during visits, likely a relative of some importance.

office
The narrator enjoys talking with persons of quality at his office, indicating it is an important part of his daily routine.

journal
The narrator records his daily activities in a journal, showing his dedication to documenting events.

Will
Will is the narrator's servant who has lost his clock with the stolen tankard, causing no further distress to the narrator.<SEP>Will is an assistant or servant of the narrator who was sent to fetch items and check on various tasks.<SEP>The Will is a legal document outlining the distribution of assets upon death.<SEP>The will is a legal document being examined by the narrator, his father, and their advisors, with discussions around its sufficiency and advice on its contents.

box of papers from Brampton
The box contains all uncle's papers and will be a source of work for the narrator.

Whitehall
Whitehall is a significant location in London that has served multiple purposes for the narrator. Primarily, it functions as an official and governmental area where various business and social activities take place. The narrator frequently visits Whitehall for meetings with officials such as Lord, conducting both work-related and social events.

There are specific instances where Whitehall serves as a venue for important matters. For example, one visit was marked by the narrator taking his wife on a water trip to this area on the 24th, which could indicate either official business or social activities. Additionally, there is mention of visiting Whitehall in the morning presumably for work-related purposes.

Whitehall also hosts significant events and meetings involving government and royal officials. It is noted as a place where important government and royal offices are located, often visited for document examinations and other formal proceedings. Furthermore, one visit was specifically for a dinner held on the premises, indicating its role in hosting official social gatherings.

In summary, Whitehall encompasses various roles including an official governmental district, a venue for business meetings with high-ranking officials, and a space for both professional duties and social events.

Exchange
The narrator visits the Exchange, likely for business matters such as meeting his uncle Wight or discussing estate matters.<SEP>Exchange is a financial institution where securities are bought and sold, indicating that the office's bills are being offered at a loss there.<SEP>The Exchange is a place the narrator visits to meet with Dr. Williams and look for an attorney to advise about their bond.

uncle Wight
Uncle Wight is mentioned as being discontented about their father and causes the narrator trouble during their meeting at the Exchange.<SEP>Uncle Wight is a family member who met with the narrator at the Exchequer and later had dinner together.<SEP>uncle Wight is another uncle of Robert, who was out of town and not available for a meeting.

my mother's
The narrator visits his mother's house where he finds his wife, aunt Bell, and Mrs. Ramsey, leading to gossip among them.

Pope's Head Alley
Mr. Hill of Cambridge is met in Pope's Head Alley with women who accompany him there.

Tavern
The narrator and Mr. Hill visit a tavern where they are offered wine, indicating it was a social place for men to meet and discuss matters.<SEP>A tavern is a place where they drank wine and beer after their journey to Woolwich.

The Jovial Crew
This play is described as the most innocent and well-performed one that the narrator has seen, offering entertainment during his visit to the theatre.

Theatre
The narrator attends a performance at the Theatre, specifically seeing "The Jovial Crew."<SEP>A venue where plays are performed, such as "Harry the 4th" which the narrator sees on the 5th day.<SEP>Theatre refers to a place where "Claracilla" was performed, different from Sir William Davenant's Opera which the speaker also attended.

my father
My father is mentioned in relation to the uncle and the discontent expressed by his son Wight.<SEP>My father is the patriarch of the family who agrees to send his daughter's servant away but refuses to have anything further to do with her. He also has accounts that are settled by the narrator.<SEP>The narrator's father visited his house and was involved in various discussions, including financial matters with Dr. Williams regarding the narrator's wife's health.

Mr. Montagu's chamber
At Mr. Montagu's chamber, the narrator hears a Frenchman play on the guitar.

Mr. George Montagu
Mr. George Montagu discusses plans with the narrator regarding a ship to carry young gentlemen to France, indicating he is involved in important decisions.

Lord Hinchingbroke
Lord Hinchingbroke and other young gentlemen are planned to travel to France by a hired vessel from Rye rather than a man of war.<SEP>Lord Hinchingbroke is a nobleman who falls ill, making the narrator worried about his condition and possible smallpox infection.

Westminster Hall
The Parliament is expected to be adjourned in Westminster Hall but is hindered for a day or two due to some matter.<SEP>Westminster Hall was the location of discussions between the two Houses about parliamentary privileges and bills.<SEP>Westminster Hall is where Samuel Pepys walked during Term time.<SEP>Westminster Hall is a location mentioned as part of the narrator's visit for some private discussions with Mrs. Michell before going to see a play.<SEP>Westminster Hall is an historic building where the text mentions walking up and down during term time.

Duke of Buckingham
The Duke of Buckingham is mentioned as someone who attempts to undermine the Lord Chancellor but fails, according to Mr. Montagu's opinion.

Lord of Bristoll
Lord of Bristol also attempts to undermine the Lord Chancellor.

King
The King is mentioned as someone who may favor Presbytery over the City's will, showing his influence in religious matters.<SEP>The King is involved in discussions regarding the Navy's financial issues with the Duke of York.

Chancellor
The Lord Chancellor is described as a person much envied by many great men, suggesting he holds significant power and influence.<SEP>Chancellor, or possibly a different individual named Jackson, is one of Samuel Pepys' tenants for Cotton closes who he had discourse with.

Lord of Sandwich
It is mentioned that it's the birthday of the Lord of Sandwich, leading to a gathering at the narrator's home with many friends present.<SEP>Lord of Sandwich refers to a nobleman who requires financial assistance for preparations related to Portugal.

Mr. Townsend and his wife
Mr. Townsend and his wife are guests at the Lord of Sandwich's birthday celebration.

Captain Isham
Captain Isham participates in the birthday celebration as well, showing his involvement in the event.<SEP>Captain Isham was one of the guests at the birthday celebration for Lord Sandwich, where they had a good time together.

Captain Ferrers lady
The captain's lady is also a guest at the celebration, indicating social standing and connections.

Mr. Pargiter, the merchant
Mr. Pargiter is a merchant who also attends the gathering at the Lord of Sandwich's home.

Samuel Pepys
Samuel Pepys is the author of the diary entry, providing details about his daily activities and observations.<SEP>Samuel Pepys is the author of the diary, detailing his daily life and various activities including work, social engagements, and purchases.<SEP>Samuel Pepys is the author of the diary entry, detailing his daily activities in August 1661.<SEP>Samuel Pepys was a Clerk of the Acts and Secretary to the Admiralty who kept a detailed diary covering various events in 1661, including financial transactions and personal observations.<SEP>Samuel Pepys is a diary writer who documents various personal and professional matters in his diary.<SEP>Samuel Pepys, the author of the diary, details various personal and professional interactions throughout the text.

Lord Sandwich
Lord Sandwich had a birthday celebration at the Wardrobe where Samuel Pepys was present with other guests.<SEP>Lord Sandwich is discussed as someone who is ill in the straits and recently recovered from an illness in Alicante.<SEP>Lord Sandwich, a nobleman, is sick in Alicante and if he should miscarry, his family's condition would be uncertain.

Mr. Townsend
Mr. Townsend was one of the guests at the birthday celebration for Lord Sandwich, where they sang songs together.<SEP>Mr. Townsend is willing to communicate any information beneficial to the narrator regarding his lordship's business.

Mrs. Ramsay
Mrs. Ramsay visited Samuel Pepys's home, dined with them and was well received by their wives.

Mr. Pargiter
Mr. Pargiter, the merchant, joined Samuel Pepys and other guests at a tavern after dinner on Lord Sandwich's birthday.

Captain Ferrers
The Captain Ferrers's wife attended the gathering with other guests and Samuel Pepys showed them ships from his houseboat.<SEP>Captain Ferrers is a person whom the narrator takes to see a play along with other young gentlemen and ladies.

my Father
Pepys's father is mentioned as being alone in Brampton and without communication since his son left, which troubles him.

Mrs. Ramsay (second mention)
Mrs. Ramsay visited Samuel and his wife again on August 1st after her first visit to the Pepys home for Lord Sandwich's birthday celebration.

Sir W. Pen
Sir W. Pen came to the Pepys house in the afternoon, drank with them, and then went away, later visited his daughter who had recently returned from Ireland.<SEP>A colleague of the narrator who accompanies him on various activities such as playing bowls, visiting Captain Lambert's house, and drinking claret with him on the 5th and 6th days.<SEP>Sir William Pen is a character mentioned in the diary who travels with Pepys and Mr. Gauden on June 1st, 1661.<SEP>Sir W. Pen is a person referenced in the counterfeit letter to whom the narrator directed his prankish message.<SEP>Sir W. Pen is a person the narrator dined with at Sir W.'s house, likely a social acquaintance.

Mr. Glassecocke (first mention)
Pepys's cousin Charles Glassecocke is mentioned as being ill and going to see his brother John, who was also dying in the country.

John Glassecocke
John Glassecocke, Pepys's cousin's brother, was dying in the country when his cousin Charles went to visit him.

White Hall
White Hall is a place where Samuel Pepys went with Sir R. Slingsby and they discussed business matters related to Tangier.<SEP>White Hall is the residence where Samuel Pepys observed the Portuguese Ambassador taking leave from the King.<SEP>White Hall is mentioned as the location where the narrator went after hearing that Lord Privy Seal was there, and later discussed bills with him.<SEP>White Hall is a place visited by Pepys for various activities including reading and walking in St. James's Park.

King Charles II
The King was expected to come to White Hall and Westminster Hall to adjourn Parliament, but Pepys did not see him due to their water journey.<SEP>King Charles II is referenced as the monarch who gave Clarendon certain grants and was seen by Pepys in a plain riding suit.

Mr. Moore
Mr. Moore visited Samuel Pepys's office and they walked into the city together, discussing business matters related to Tangier.<SEP>Mr. Moore is mentioned as someone the narrator met at Lady's residence and discussed business with.<SEP>An associate or friend who accompanies the narrator to various places on this day, including visits and drinks.<SEP>Mr. Moore accompanied the narrator to Westminster Hall on a legal matter.

Dr. Thomas Pepys
Dr. Thomas Pepys met Samuel Pepys at the Wardrobe and was described as a "silly talking fellow" but good-natured.

Roger Pepys
Pepys intended to meet with Roger Pepys for counsel about the Assizes beginning in Cambridge and Huntingdon.<SEP>Roger Pepys is a close acquaintance of Samuel Pepys, who accompanied him on some journeys and attended church with him.<SEP>Roger Pepys is referred to as the speaker's cousin who was going up to Parliament House during term time.

Mr. Salisbury
Mr. Salisbury was a limner who had improved his skills rapidly, and Samuel Pepys took him out for drinks at Hercules Pillars.

Mr. Whore (first mention)
Mr. Whore was a friend of Mr. Salisbury's whom Samuel Pepys met during their visit to the tavern and drank with them.

Assizes in Cambridge and Huntingdon
The Assizes were scheduled to begin at Cambridge and Huntingdon, prompting Samuel Pepys to seek information about when they would start.

Tangier
Pepys discussed business matters related to Tangier with Mr. Moore and Sir R. Slingsby during their office visit.

Sir R. Ford's house
Sir R. Ford's house was visited by Samuel Pepys and Sir R. Slingsby for its potential addition to the office.<SEP>Sir R. Ford's house is an office that Samuel Pepys and his colleagues are considering adding to their existing office space.

Pepys Family
The Pepys family includes Samuel, his wife, and their father, involved in various activities and events together.<SEP>The Pepys Family refers to the group of people including Samuel Pepys, his wife, father, and friends who interact within their personal and professional lives.

Father
Father refers to Samuel's father who went to Brampton, providing help when needed.<SEP>The father of the narrator, with whom he meets at his home.<SEP>Father is mentioned as a family member who came to dine with the narrator and others on the 29th afternoon.<SEP>The father is mentioned as someone who has a significant amount of estate that could not easily be given away due to lack of present possession, indicating financial responsibilities.

Lady Batten
Lady Batten is mentioned alongside other ladies during the visit to "Bartholomew Fayre."

Bartholomew Fair
Bartholomew Fair is the event visited by Pepys and others during their day out.

Bartholomew Fayre
"Bartholomew Fayre" is a fair that was acted upon, indicating some form of entertainment or performance there.

Moorefields
Moorefields is the place where wrestling matches were observed by Samuel Pepys and Sir W. Pen.

Sir William Batten
Sir William Batten is a character mentioned in association with other visits and activities, including the office and the fair.<SEP>A person whom the narrator visits for advice, who has come from Chatham with his wife on the 7th day.

Lord's Day
Lord's Day refers to Sunday, on which Samuel attended church services.<SEP>The Lord's Day refers to Sunday, the day on which Samuel Pepys attended church and engaged in other activities.<SEP>The Lord's Day refers to Sunday, on which the narrator stayed at home and engaged in various activities.

Portuguese Ambassador
The Portuguese Ambassador visited White Hall to take leave of the King, indicating a diplomatic event.

Duke of York
The Duke of York is mentioned in connection with discussions about ships and their delays.<SEP>The Duke of York is a high-ranking nobleman who had plans to travel down with his fleet, prompting the narrator to arrange stowage for supplies on the King's Yacht.<SEP>The Duke of York is a recipient of the letters written by Sir G. Carteret and others regarding the office conditions.<SEP>The Duke of York is a nobleman who is troubled by the condition of the Navy and will speak to the King and Council about it.

Gray's Inn Walk
Gray's Inn Walk is noted for its fine ladies and was visited by Samuel Pepys alone.

Duke
The Duke is involved in correspondence regarding the delay of ships, leading to an examination with Sir Williams Batten.

Hooker's Ecclesiastical Polity
Hooker's Ecclesiastical Polity is a book recommended by Mr. Chetwind that Samuel Pepys intends to purchase.<SEP>Hooker's Ecclesiastical Polity is a book given to Pepys by Mr. Moore, which he intends to read with care.

The Duke of York
The Duke of York is mentioned in connection with the ships' delays and the embassy to the Queen.

Theodore Goodgroome
Theodore Goodgroome is Samuel Pepys' singing master who accompanied him during a singing practice session.

St. Dunstan's-in-the-West
St. Dunstan's-in-the-West church is noted for its collection during a fire event.

I
The narrator of the text, an individual who engages in various activities such as meeting with friends and family, attending events, and conducting business.<SEP>The narrator expresses anger at their father and later deals with a maid named Jane leaving, as well as various personal and familial matters.

J. Holcroft
A cozen (cousin) of the narrator who is planning to go into the country the next day and accompanies the narrator and others to a tavern called "Bear."

Bear tavern
The tavern visited by the narrator, his father, J. Holcroft, and brother Tom for drinks.

Lord Crew
A nobleman who hosts the narrator for dinner and discusses military service with him.<SEP>Lord Crew is a nobleman whom Pepys dines with at his home, discussing matters of naval service and young noblemen entering the military profession.<SEP>Lord Crew, a nobleman, dines with the narrator and other individuals at Sir H. Wright's house.

Queen Elizabeth's time
Refers to a historical period during which certain social customs were observed, such as one young nobleman waiting at another's back until he came of age.

Young Lord of Kent
A young nobleman who waited upon his uncle, Lord Bedford, at table when the Earldom of Kent was transferred to him by inheritance.

Lord Bedford
An older nobleman who served as a host and mentor figure to the Young Lord of Kent, allowing him to sit in his place after he came of age.

Harry the 4th
A play that is being performed at the Theatre and observed by the narrator.

Southwark
A district in London where the narrator walks to after leaving the theatre on the 5th day.

Wardrobe
A place of work for the narrator, where he conducts business and spends time with colleagues such as Sir William Pen and Sir Richard Slingsby.<SEP>Wardrobe is where the narrator dines with his wife, children, and then visits Lady's bedside for conversation.<SEP>The Wardrobe refers to a specific location where the narrator met with Lord Slingsby and his brother.<SEP>Wardrobe is a place in London where the narrator had meetings with his Lady and others.

Westminster
Another location where the narrator dines alone with Ned Dickering on the 5th day.

Office
The workplace of the narrator, used for conducting business and other tasks such as playing bowls games.<SEP>Office refers to a place where Samuel and his colleagues work, facing financial difficulties and potential changes in tenure.<SEP>The narrator's workplace where he spends part of his day on the 29th.<SEP>The office refers to the workplace of the narrator, where business matters were discussed and work was done.

Sir William Pen
A colleague of the narrator who assists him in various activities including playing bowls and drinking.

Sir Richard Slingsby
A friend or acquaintance of the narrator, whom he visits for a night of drinking and socializing on the 5th day.

Bowls ally
The location where the narrator and Sir Richard Slingsby engage in a game of bowls.

Mrs. Holland
The wife of Mr. Holland, whom the narrator pays money to and dines with at her house.

Captain Lambert
A captain of a ship who is later promoted from Lieutenant to Captain of Norwich during the narrator's visit on the 6th day.<SEP>Captain Lambert is a host who welcomed the narrator and his wife to his turret-garden and needlework exhibition.

Lieutenant Lambert
The lieutenant, now made a captain, whom the narrator visits at Greenwich with Sir William Pen on the 6th day.

Greenwich
A location visited by the narrator and Captain Lambert to discuss ship matters and enjoy music.

Globe
The Globe Theatre where the narrator sees a performance of "Bartholomew Faire" on the 8th day.

Bartholomew Faire
A play being performed at the Globe Theatre which the narrator attends and finds admirably acted, though with some criticism for its language content.

Mr. Holland
The husband of Mrs. Holland, whom the narrator pays money to in his absence on the 7th day.

Brampton
Brampton appears to be a significant place with multiple connections in this narrative. It serves various roles and contexts:

First, Brampton is associated with family matters, particularly involving the father and uncle. In one context, Pepys's father resides alone in Brampton, leading to concern due to lack of correspondence. Additionally, Samuel's father visits Brampton possibly to see his uncle Robert, who might be unwell. The narrative also mentions a plan or expectation that Samuel's father will settle there with his mother.

Second, Brampton is linked to the narrator's personal journey and interests. On one occasion, the narrator visits Brampton for unspecified reasons, which could be either personal or business-related. There was an interest in purchasing land and houses there but finding it too costly. Another instance involves a visit where the narrator finds his father well upon returning from London, learning that his uncle had died the previous day.

Lastly, Brampton is referenced as the location where the narrator returns home for supper and bed, indicating its significance as a residence or place of rest. These various roles suggest that Brampton plays multiple important parts in the narrative—being associated with family dynamics, personal interests, and daily routines.

In summary, Brampton is not just a geographical location but holds multifaceted importance within the narrative, serving as a backdrop for family interactions, business ventures, and personal reflections.

Captain Lambert's house
A home visited by the narrator and Sir William Pen after their trip to Greenwich where they have a good time drinking and socializing.

Mr. Rawlinson
An uncle figure to the narrator who offers him business advice and discusses potential purchases with him at his house on the 8th day.<SEP>Mr. Rawlinson is an uncle of Robert, who provides advice to the narrator about purchasing land.

Uncle Wight
The uncle of the narrator from whom he received advice to answer a letter on his behalf, offering him an opportunity for financial gain through land purchase on the 8th day.<SEP>Uncle Wight is an uncle whom the narrator meets at Mr. Rawlinson's house for reading a will and discussing family matters.

Uncle Robert
Another relative of the narrator who offers him financial advice through a letter, proposing a land purchase opportunity that benefits both parties' estates.

Sir W. Batten
Sir W. Batten is a person from whom Samuel Pepys had to borrow money, specifically £40.<SEP>Sir William Batten is a character mentioned who was part of the group traveling on the first day of June with Samuel Pepys, but later left for Whitsuntide celebrations.<SEP>Sir William Batten is a person who hosted the narrator for dinner on multiple occasions during this period.

Walthamstow
Walthamstow is a place visited by Samuel Pepys for some social activity.

The Tamer Tamed
"The Tamer Tamed" is a play that was performed at the Theatre and impressed Samuel Pepys.

Mrs. Pen
Mrs. Pen is an acquaintance of Samuel Pepys, whom he met for the first time since her return from Ireland.

Worminghaye
Worminghaye, or Impington, is where Samuel Pepys spent the night after his journey from Cambridge.

Coach
The coach is a mode of transportation used by Samuel Pepys when traveling to Walthamstow.

Ware
Ware is a place Samuel Pepys passed through while riding to Walthamstow.

fellmonger
A fellmonger, or dealer in hides, was someone whom Samuel Pepys had an interaction with during his journey.

Quaker
The Quaker is a person who Samuel Pepys met and conversed with during his trip to Cambridge.

Castle Hill
Castle Hill is the location where judges were holding assizes when Samuel Pepys visited.

Rose
The Rose may refer to a pub or establishment where Samuel Pepys and others socialized after dinner.

Trinity Hall
Trinity Hall is the location of Dr. Thomas Pepys' residence, where Samuel Pepys dined with his brother and Claxton.

Barkway
Barkway is a place mentioned as part of Samuel Pepys' journey from Walthamstow to Cambridge.

Trice Thomas
Thomas Trice is someone Samuel Pepys dined with at Mr. Phillips' place in Huntingdon.

Stanton
Stanton is the name of a place mentioned as part of the route while staying in Huntingdon because of rain.

Huntingdon
Huntingdon is a place where Samuel Pepys stayed for some time due to rain and where he borrowed a coat from a man.<SEP>Huntingdon is a location mentioned as where Mr. Phillips was staying last night when the narrator went to visit him.

Tom Pepys
Tom Pepys is the brother of Samuel Pepys who visited him in Cambridge.

Impington
Impington is where Samuel Pepys spent the night after his journey from Cambridge.<SEP>Impington is the location associated with Uncle [Talbot Pepys], who was born there in 1583 and lived until his death in 1666.

Nightingale
Nightingale is the name of someone whose house is described as pretty and where Samuel Pepys sought information about his business.

Graveley
Graveley is a place where Samuel Pepys went to meet with Chancler and Jackson, among other activities.

Talbot
Uncle Talbot refers to Samuel Pepys' uncle who accompanied him to church on Sunday.

Church
Church is a place of worship where Samuel Pepys attended services and received a sermon from the parson.

Parson
The parson refers to the clergyman who preached at the church service, addressing Samuel Pepys by title and affectionately.

Dr. Gunning
Dr. Gunning, a member of the University of Cambridge, is mentioned by Roger Pepys as one of those who were highly regarded but not well-liked by others due to their academic standing.

Huntingdon's Parliament
Huntingdon's Parliament is a reference to the political body that had been engaging in contentious activities according to Roger Pepys' account.

David Widger
David Widger is an individual who produced a transcription from Samuel Pepys' diary for publication.

The Diary of Samuel Pepys
The Diary of Samuel Pepys, M.A., F.R.S. is an unabbreviated and edited version of Samuel Pepys' personal account, transcribed by the Rev. Mynors Bright and including notes by Lord Braybrooke.

My Lady
My Lady refers to Sir W. Batten's wife or another noblewoman accompanying him during their trip.<SEP>My Lady is a woman the narrator dined with, presumably his wife or a close female associate.

Whitsuntide
Whitsuntide is a Christian feast celebrating Pentecost, occurring about seven weeks after Easter Sunday or forty days after the Resurrection, which Pepys mentions as an event he and others are going to keep in June 1661.

Mr. Gauden
Mr. Gauden is another individual traveling with Pepys and Sir W. Pen to Woolwich on June 1st, 1661.

Woolwich
Woolwich is a town in southeast London where the group stopped to give orders for ships' readiness and dined at the tavern there.

Deptford
Deptford is another location near Woolwich where Pepys and his companions gave similar orders to the ships before returning home.

Redriffe
Redriffe is the location of the half-way house visited by Pepys during his journey home from Deptford.

Captain Poole's Tavern
Captain Poole's Tavern in Woolwich was a place where Pepys and others dined on June 1st, 1661.

Half-Way House
The half-way house in Redriffe was a stopping place where travelers could rest and find food or drink during their journeys.

Whitsunday
Whitsunday, also known as Pentecost, is celebrated on the 50th day after Easter Sunday. Pepys mentions attending church services on this date in June 1661.

Mr. Mills
Mr. Mills is the preacher who gave a sermon at church on Whitsunday, which was deemed appropriate for that day.

Greatorex
Greatorex is a person whom Pepys expected to join him for dinner but instead arrived unexpectedly and stayed until late in the evening discussing mathematics with him.

Lord Braybrooke's Notes
Lord Braybrooke's notes are additional material included with Samuel Pepys' diary, enhancing its historical value.

Henry B. Wheatley
Henry B. Wheatley is an individual who added to the edited and published version of Samuel Pepys' diary, contributing to its comprehensive nature.

Lord Abbot Montagu
Lord Abbot Montagu is a nobleman mentioned in the text as someone whose presence or absence affects travel plans for other noblemen.

data.entity_name: Mr. Young's Place in the Wardrobe
data.content:
Mr. Young's Place in the Wardrobe
The place in the Wardrobe referred to by Pepys was an important position he wanted to secure, possibly related to financial management and record-keeping.

Lord Hinchinbroke
Lord Hinchinbroke is a nobleman mentioned who had planned travel with his brother but did not arrive as expected, causing Pepys to change his travel plans.

Lord Hinchinbroke's brother
Lord Hinchinbroke's brother was mentioned as someone who had planned travel with his brother but did not arrive.

Mr. Turner's Lodgings
Mr. Turner's lodgings were an accommodation that the Comptroller suggested switching for himself and others during their visit near the office, but the idea was ultimately abandoned due to unsuitable houses.

Bear Tavern
Bear tavern was the place Pepys and his companions visited after leaving The Temple to enjoy drinks and company before heading to Lord Crew's for dinner.

The Temple
The Temple is a historic location in London where Pepys visits his father on June 4th, 1661.

Business
Business refers to financial and work-related issues that Samuel Pepys needs to manage, but there are no specific details on the nature of his business.<SEP>Various business matters, including family estate management and Tom's trade responsibilities, are noted as troubling for the narrator on this day.

Court
Court refers to a place where Samuel Pepys encounters issues such as emulacion and drinking habits among people.

Tom
Tom is Samuel Pepys's brother who is left in charge of his father's trade, raising concerns about Tom's capability.<SEP>Tom is the narrator's brother who might be involved in his father's trade and is of interest to Mr. Evans for marriage purposes.

Benevolence
Benevolence is a voluntary contribution made by the subjects to their sovereign, but it causes discontent in the community according to Samuel's diary.

Serjeant Bernard
Serjeant Bernard is a person who has returned home and is mentioned in the context of the narrator's supper plans.<SEP>Serjeant Bernard is a person who has returned home and may offer additional legal advice or assistance.

Quakers
Quakers are mentioned as still present and growing, indicating religious groups influencing the society during this period.

Strange and fatal fevers
Strange and fatal fevers refer to health issues prevalent during Samuel Pepys's time, affecting many people negatively.

Emulacion
Emulacion refers to a state of rivalry or competition among individuals at Court, leading to social and possibly political tensions.

Alchymist
Alchymist is a comedy by Ben Jonson that Samuel Pepys mentions but does not read or perform in.

Goody Gorum
Goody Gorum is a person at whose house discussions occurred during the narrator's visit on the 21st.<SEP>Goody Gorum is a woman the narrator visited with Thos. Trice and Mr. Phillips for drinks.

Jane Perkin
Jane Perkin, along with the maid, is a source of information about the narrator's aunt's behavior.<SEP>Jane Perkin is mentioned as someone the narrator uses for information about his aunt's behavior, indicating she provides insights into family dynamics.

Mr. Phillips
Mr. Phillips is one of the narrator's friends who accompanied him to Mother----- for supper and drinking on the 20th.<SEP>Mr. Phillips is a person the narrator visited at Huntingdon but could not find because he had left the previous night.

Robert Ethell
Robert Ethell is another friend whom the narrator visited in town on the 20th.

Dr. Symcottes
Dr. Symcottes is a friend whom the narrator visited during his walk in town on the 20th.

Mr. Vinter
Mr. Vinter is one of the narrator's friends mentioned as being with him during his afternoon activities on the 20th.
